You were trying to modify a immutable variable (`balance`) as cchantep told you.

Here is a trivial example that may get you started:

    // Start writing your ScalaFiddle code here
    case class JointAccount (balance: Long) {
      def displayBalance = println(balance)
      def withDrawl(amt: Int) = JointAccount(balance - amt)
      def deposit(amt: Int) = JointAccount(balance + amt)
    }
    
    val a = JointAccount(1000)
    
    println(a)
    a.displayBalance
    val b = (a withDrawl 500) deposit 500
    println(b)

You can play with it here https://scalafiddle.io/sf/f8Usa20/5

`val` -&gt; `var`

Also, your deposit and withdrawl functions do the same thing so I&#39;ve fixed that

```
class JointAccount (var balance: Long) {

 def displayBalance = println(balance)

 def withDrawl(amt: Int) = {
   balance -=amt
 }

 def deposit(amt: Int) = {
   balance +=amt
 }
}

val x = new JointAccount(123L)

x.deposit(4)
x.displayBalance
```

[See it working live here][1]

I must say though, this is very Java and not at all Scala, in terms of how you&#39;ve chosen to implement it. Scala best practices recommend avoiding mutable variables and functions that return a `Unit`. Here&#39;s an example re-written version of your code:

```
case class JointAccount (balance: Long) {
 def withDrawl(amt: Int) = this.copy(balance = balance - amt)

 def deposit(amt: Int) = this.copy(balance = balance + amt)
 // alternative: def deposit(amt: Int) = JointAccount(balance + amt)
}

def displayBalance(ja: JointAccount) = println(ja.balance)

val x = JointAccount(123L)

displayBalance(x.deposit(4))
```

[See it working live here][2]

In Scala, it is much better to have functions inside a class either return a number (in your case) or a new class which has an updated value.


  [1]: https://scastie.scala-lang.org/USoXoVZSTdWpbNQLLgthEg
  [2]: https://scastie.scala-lang.org/6hz8bRTgSHSApomLXrmoLw

