If I understand you correctly, you want each section separated by a &quot;===========&quot; boundary to be its unique dict in a list of dicts.
You did not provide any code, but seeing you employ this regex to find you key/value pairs

    r&#39;^(\w+)\s*(.*)&#39;

I assume you grab the two groups and simply pass their respective values as `newDict[match.group(1)] = match.group(2)`

The issue comes down to how you are reading the data. In this approach, I would simply read the file line by line, but since your values can be multiline, I am already unsure how you even get the correct groupings from the regex you provided. &quot;(.*)&quot; should be greedy as hell and return you much more than what you would like.

Provided all line-jumps are marked by &quot;\&quot;, you could write a regex that can take this into account, like this:
Replace &quot;(.*)&quot; with &quot;([\w,=]+(\s\\\s?[\w,=]+)?)&quot;

However, I would probably just make certain adjustments to the text file as I read it in, to have all datapoints stored on a single line before iterating over it and capturing with your previous regex.
Added bonus: 
You can add a line in the iteration function that matches &quot;=========&quot; and initialize a new dictionary while adding the old to the list.

       import re
       final_list = []
    
       def makeDict(fl, data):
            kvPattern = re.compile(r&#39;^(\w+)\s*(.*)&#39;)
            newDict = {}
            for line in data:
                if line.startswith(&quot;=============&quot;):
                    fl.append(newDict)
                    newDict = {}
                elif kvPattern.search(line):
                    match = kvPattern.search(line)
                    newDict[match.group(1)] = match.group(2)
    
            return fl
    
        final_list = makeDict(final_list, data)

If you feel cocky, you can use &quot;else&quot; instead of &quot;elif&quot;, too.
Or even better, wrap the whole thing in Try-blocks to check wether any datapoints don&#39;t match your regex pattern
